<h2> The Story Behind Karma Grove </h2>

<p>
  Joshua Montross founded Karma Grove on his own personal philosophy, that justice and charity aren't so different, and that business doesn't have to exploitative. Here's his story:
</p>

<p>
<blockquote><i>
  As a sophomore in college, I was a distressed international business student. I was anxious at the prospect of entering a world of such growing gaps between the rich and the poor.  I had come to college thinking I would one day be a banker, and I left with a desire to create a farm to table system that empowers local economies and shrinks the wealth gap.  I went to work as a programmer, biding my time and gaining the worldly knowledge I would need to fulfill this quest calling from within.
</i>
</blockquote>
</p>
<p>
   <blockquote><i>
    I was in Washington, DC and I had grown disillusioned with the economic doctrine of rational self-interest that was taught to me in my economics courses.  I also felt that the <a target="new" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal%E2%80%93agent_problem"> agency problem </a> could only be alleviated using a corporate structure that did not separate owner and worker or corporate interest and community interest.</i>
   </blockquote>
 </p>

<p>
 <blockquote>
 <i>
  I began spending more and more time at the Gelman Libaray at GWU. I was reading a lot of philosophy and after entering a Judaic Philosophy contest for prize money, I became intrigued with the semantic similarity between charity and justice in the Hebrew language.  I ended up writing an essay, and developed the concept for a business that allowed its customers to give away half of the profits, the employees to give away thirty percent, to keep ten percent for growth, and to give ten percent to employees as a bonus on top of wages.  I initially wanted to form a cafe and call it Karma Cafe and replace the Starbucks in the basement of Gelman.
</i>
</blockquote>
</p>

<p>
  <blockquote>
  <i>
  I did not win the philosophy contest, and for a long time,  Karma Grove only existed in my writing and dreams.
</i>
</blockquote>
</p>

<p>
  <blockquote>
    <i>
  Following stints as a project manager and software engineer in the District, I moved to California in 2011. While there, one of my good friends, <b><%= link_to "Magan Biggs", "https://twitter.com/maganbunny" %></b>, taught me to make (particularly delicious) granola bars.  I tweaked her recipe and made it a little more to my taste, and what I began to call Joy Coins were born.
</i>
</blockquote>
<p>

  <p>
    <blockquote>
      <i>
  I named them Joy Coins because I had a nice roommate named Joy who suggested I stop using butter to make them vegetarian.  My friends loved them and I realized I could combine my passion, my Karma Cafe business model, with my tasty treats that people were already enjoying. Later this same recipe is what became <b><%= link_to "Karma Coins", "/Karma-Coin-Facts" %></b> when I began to market them and sell under the name Karma Grove.
</i>
</blockquote>
</p>

<p>
  <blockquote>
  <i>
   Another year goes by and I'm laid off in December 2012.  January 2013 the karmagrove application is created on github and continues to be an open source community effort.  I also began selling my Joy Coins at a cafe in Santa Cruz around this time in January 2013.  Some time shortly after I started calling them Karma Coins, planting the corporation in the logos of karma in hopes of unraveling many of the troubles we have created.
</i>
  </blockquote>
</p>

<p>

  <blockquote>
    <i>
       For the intermittent bake sales that occurred throughout 2013, I would take the cash collected from the sales and give 80% of it to <%= link_to "Grey Bears", "http://www.greybears.org/items-needed/" %>.  The receipts are all proudly displayed on the <%= link_to "twitter feed", "http://twitter.com/karmagrove" %>.  Grey Bears is our first partner, feeding the elderly and hungry in Santa Cruz using money from purchases made to feed other Santa Cruzians.  I began to make relationships with other non-profits I truly appreciate, including <%= link_to "Elephants and Bees", "http://elephantsandbees.com/" %> and <%= link_to "Nuru", "http://www.nuruinternational.org/" %>.
    </i>
  </blockquote>
</p>

<h2>to know where you are going, know where you are from </h2>
<p>
  So Karma Grove's background. This site is an experiment from Joshua's heart of hearts.  His dream of a paradoxical business, giving away 80% of its profits and having no shareholders, can continue to grow and benefit us and our earth without taking advantage of anyone; or increasing the wealth divide.  It is a snowball that we push up a hill.   Khalil Gibran tells us that all great truths are a paradox.
</p>

<p>
  We hope you enjoyed reading a little bit of history on how this all came to be.  We're here now, and we know it is just the beginning of something great. This site will serve as a marketplace of conscious commerce, flowing money to those in need in our glocal community.
</p>

